    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-02-27T18:38:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-02-27T18:38:00-05:00" n="48"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d48">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_FE1">FE</gloss> files, lot 55 D 128, tab 88</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Joint Chiefs of Staff</gloss> to the
                        Commander in Chief Far East (<persName corresp="#p_RGMB1" type="to"
                            >Ridgway</persName>)</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d48fn1">This telegram was initialed in draft by <persName
                            corresp="#p_THS1">Truman</persName>; draft copy is in file
                        795.00/2–2752.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret<lb/>operational immediate</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-02-27T18:38:00-05:00"
                            >February 27, 1952—6:38 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> 902160. From <gloss target="#t_JCS1"
                        >JCS</gloss>. Reur CX 64343 [<hi rend="italic">64342</hi>].<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d48fn2">Not printed, but see <ref target="#d44fn2">footnote 2 p.
                            67</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>You are authorized to make it entirely clear to Commies that <gloss
                            target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> refusal to accept Soviet Union as a member
                        of Neutral Supervisory Commission is absolutely firm and irrevocable. There
                        is no propaganda problem in regard to our position on this question.
                        Therefore, we consider amplication of basis for <gloss target="#t_UNC1"
                            >UNC</gloss> rejection of Soviet Union not necessary beyond that
                        required to make it clear to Commie Del that <gloss target="#t_UNC1"
                            >UNC</gloss> position this regard is entirely firm.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>We believe that a position along the fol lines might be set forth by the
                            <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> Del at your discretion if you
                        believe agreement can be advanced thereby. The <gloss target="#t_UNC1"
                            >UNC</gloss> initially proposed that inspection teams be composed of the
                        belligerents of both sides. This proposal was rejected by the Communists.
                        The Communist proposal for neutral supervisory agency consisting of neutral
                        nations acceptable to both sides was accepted by <gloss target="#t_UNC1"
                            >UNC</gloss>, but the Communists failed to comply with the terms of
                        their own proposal. As a solution, the <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss>
                        could propose that an armistice supervisory organ and inspection teams be
                        constituted to consist of nations selected by each side regardless of their
                        combatant status in the Korean hostilities. <gloss target="#t_UNC1"
                            >UNC</gloss> Del should make clear that under this proposal it would
                        feel free to select any countries participating in hostilities <pb
                            facs="0106" n="72" xml:id="pg_72"/> under <gloss target="#t_UNC1"
                            >UNC</gloss>, which would include the US and Commies would have similar
                        rights to include USSR.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
